tspan.tspan: Mark Torrey
The surface of the world has become an uncertain place.
International shipping is forced under the ocean,
carried out by submarines fitted out for transporting
cargo. The
Prospect
is one such sub, p
iloted by a small
crew that fights a daily battle to keep their rusting
boat from dropping into the depths. It's just another
grimy job, until they are inexplicably pursued across
great expanses of ocean by a military submarine with an
aggression far out of proportion to the basic work of
logistics. The
Prospect's
captain and her crew are
forced to push their machine to the very edge of its
capabilities to survive long enough to make their
delivery.
With a heritage that is equal parts 1960s submarine
movie and 1970s trucker movie,
By Sound Alone
both
leverages the power of confined spaces and dangerous
operations that have always been the meat of compelling
submarine stories. At the same, it time breaks new
ground with a setting of a fictional world where
submarines are a critical part of global
infrastructure, while never deviating from a commitment
to realistic submarine mechanics and operations.
